          "title": "The courtroom — Israel as Yahweh's witness",
          "body": "At 43:8-13 the chapter's mode shifts dramatically from personal comfort to formal legal contest. The nations are summoned; their gods are put on trial. The question before the court is epistemological and historical: 'Who among them can declare this and proclaim to us the former things?' (43:9). The 'former things' are prior prophetic announcements of historical events that only Yahweh could have made in advance and seen fulfilled. The gods of the nations have no such track record; their witnesses, if any present themselves, cannot establish their deities' claims. By contrast, Israel is commissioned: 'You are My witnesses, declares the LORD, and My servant whom I have chosen, so that you may know and believe Me and understand that I am He' (43:10). The purpose of the witness-commission is threefold: knowledge (*yada*), belief (*aman*, the root of 'amen'), and understanding (*bin*). These are not merely intellectual outcomes but the transformation of a people whose spiritual blindness was diagnosed in 43:8. The monotheistic assertion of 43:10-11 is the most compressed in the Old Testament: before Yahweh no god was formed; after Him none will exist; 'I, even I, am the LORD, and there is no savior besides Me.' Peter Craigie and John Oswalt (NICOT) both note that this is not henotheism (one god among others who happens to be stronger) but genuine ontological monotheism — there is no divine being in any category except Yahweh. Israel's witness-vocation is to embody this claim in history."
