          "body": "The announcement of 43:14-21 is the chapter's climactic promise. Yahweh appeals to the Exodus as the paradigmatic act of salvation (43:16-17 alludes directly to the parting of the Red Sea and the drowning of Pharaoh's army), but then issues a stunning command: 'Do not call to mind the former things, or ponder things of the past. Behold, I will do something new, now it will spring forth' (43:18-19). This is not a cancellation of the Exodus from Israel's memory — the rest of Isaiah (and the Psalms) commend remembering what God has done. The command is comparative: the new act will be so surpassingly greater that the Exodus will no longer be the primary reference point. The specific content of the 'new thing' is a roadway in the wilderness and rivers in the desert — the wilderness that swallowed a generation becomes provisioned terrain. Creation itself responds: jackals and ostriches glorify God because of the water He provides for His chosen people (43:20). The new exodus is ecological and cosmic, not merely geopolitical. The New Testament trajectories of this promise are significant: John the Baptist prepares 'the way of the LORD' in the wilderness (Isaiah 40:3; Matthew 3:3); Jesus speaks of living water (John 4:10-14; 7:37-39); Revelation 21-22 portrays the new Jerusalem with a river of the water of life. Isaiah 43:19 seeds a canonical thread that terminates in the new creation."
